---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const title = 'Fluent in Fine';
const date = '2026';
---

<Layout title={`${title} — your name`} description="A poem about what okay feels like, and what it costs to lose the hurt.">
  <article class="poem-page">
    <h1 class="poem-page-title">{title}</h1>
    <div class="poem-page-date">{date}</div>

    <div class="poem-body">
      <p>Let me tell you what okay feels like —
not relief, not arrival,

not the exhale at the end of something hard.

It feels like reaching for a scar

and finding the skin so new, so sealed,

you can't remember what the wound revealed —

only that it did.
And the smoothness indicts you.

Asks what you did with all that pain.

Whether you deserved to lose it.</p>

      <p>Because if the ache was the truth of you —

if the hurt was the proof, the root,

the only thing that ever said

something real lives here,

something that bleeds when it's cut,

something that feels what it feels and doesn't shut —
then what is this quiet?</p>

      <p>This morning I woke up

and nothing in me was screaming

and I sat with that silence

like someone left at a table

where the other person just didn't come back —

and you don't know yet

if you've been abandoned

or spared.</p>

      <p>And I don't know.

I still don't know.</p>

      <p>Because okay is the story

survivors tell themselves

so the hurt had a reason —

I burned through every season of that pain,

and something was learned in the burning,

and I came through changed

but not hollow, not gutted, not drained —</p>

      <p>but I've felt what it costs to stay.

And nothing that heavy

just lifts.</p>

      <p>So either I'm lying

or I left something in the wreckage —

some essential, bleeding,

unflinching part of me

that knew how to reckon

with what things were worth,

that knew how to measure the weight of the hurt

without flinching —</p>

      <p>and now I'm just

fluent in fine.</p>

      <p>Fluent in fine.</p>

      <p>Speaking it so naturally,

so quietly, so daily,

I've lost the thread

between the woman who was barely,

barely holding —

and the woman who says

I'm okay now
like she means it.

Like she even knows what she means.</p>

      <p>That's the thing about the wound —

when it goes quiet

you don't celebrate.</p>

      <p>You grieve it.</p>

      <p>You press your hands to every hollow

where the hurt used to breathe,

where it used to live and heave and need —

and you ask —</p>

      <p>did I heal

or did something leave without my permission,

slip out in the night

and take the part of me that bled

and knew

and felt

and was real —</p>

      <p>and the silence doesn't answer.</p>

      <p>It just sits there,

smooth as new skin

where the scar used to be,</p>

      <p>and you're supposed to call that
healing.</p>
    </div>

    <nav class="poem-nav">
      <span></span>
      <a href="/poems/the-other-door">The Other Door →</a>
    </nav>
  </article>
</Layout>
